course.title: Beautiful Andromeda UI - Intro Course
course.description: This is an intro course for Beautiful Andromeda UI  that tells you exactly what you need to do to score a 5. To score a 5, you need to know how to code well, design well, and follow the task instructions correctly.

contents.body: **Andromeda** is already *so massive* that it‚Äôs now ready to welcome even more stars into orbit! **Beautiful Andromeda UI is one of the most important projects of our lifetime, and we need your help creating beautiful UIs and generating "** Golden Responses**" for the improved prompts you'll be crafting.**

In this project, your goal is to create a "**Golden Response**" for the paraphrased target prompt. You achieve this by writing your own code **and providing a golden code-only response**. Such a response contains a professional UI similar to the websites of 2025 Fortune 500 companies. **How cool is that?**

Important update: as different from what‚Äôs shown in task walkthrough video above, you‚Äôll evaluate **3 SOTA model responses** instead of 2. A **Golden Response** is a reply with an exceptionally appealing and well-designed UI that fully satisfies the prompts user's request. Not only does it look stunning, but it also functions far better than the "Claude 4 Sonnet Extended / GPT 4.1 / Gemini 2.5 Pro ." generated code for to the same initial prompt. Additionally, it has the polished, professional quality you'd expect from a commercial website. **Before starting your task, you should always look for commercial websites that are relevant to the prompt and make sure your UI looks at least as good if not better.** **For each task you will:** 1. Paraphrase the provided seed prompt (5-10 min) 2. Pick the best response (15 min) 3. Provide a true golden code-only response (3-5 hrs) 4. Verify your response with Vercel 5. Answer the question: ‚ÄùIs this the last and final turn as you generated a golden response (a response that is scored >= 4 for all three dimensions)?‚Äù 6. Collect data on the Golden Response and reevaluate (post process supervision) 7. Review Your Work Using The Quality Control Spec Doc For Attempters **To score a 5, you need to do well in:** 1. **Following Prompt Instructions:** following all implicit and explicit instructions provided by the prompt in. 2. **Coding Quality:** rewriting the code following the right specifications 3. **Design Quality:** making sure the website design looks visually impressive, like you would see it on a Fortune 500 website. In the following sections, we will go in depth on each of these categories.

sections.title: Before Coding Instructions - How to score a 5/5

contents.body: **1.üí´ Acknowledge Task parameters and paraphrase the prompt**

Only change the semantics. For more information see this website:[ Pragmatics vs. Semantics](https://en.wikiversity.org/wiki/Semantics_vs_pragmatics) **3c**: Ensure that it doesn't start with "design, build, construct, create, implement" and 2) that it sounds natural as if written by a human. **3d**: Paste the paraphrased prompt in the prompt input box. This will be your target prompt throughout the task.

sections.title: Golden Code Quality - How to score a 5/5

contents.body: **3.WRITE THE GOLDEN RESPONSE (Code Quality)** **üí´ Edit the response code and text to make it a Golden Code-Only Response**. Make sure it looks like a commercial website (look up commercial websites related to the prompt and then use that as inspiration). You will spend 3 to 5 hours hours fixing the code till it generates a production ready UI.

**Step 1: You will write your own Golden Response by rewriting the response we call this doing a Golden Rewrite.** **1a:** Look up a commercial website that you will use as a reference for your golden response. **1b:** Expect to do rewrites 9/10 times. The model sucks at implementing functionality. **1c**: React files need to be self-contained (you cannot have a separate CSS file imported) and must always export default components. All the styling needs to be in the file. **Step 2: Validate that the response is feature complete and satisfies the response completely using the**[\*\* UI Rubric Generator\*\*](https://ui-req-gen.vercel.app/generate-requirements) **2a:** Validate that it contains all features requested in the prompt. **THIS IS REALLY IMPORTANT** #### #### **Input your prompt into the tool** #### **** #### **2b:** Validate that all features work as expected. Explicit features requested in the prompt must be fully functional.¬†**THIS IS ALSO REALLY IMPORTANT** #### **Verify the requirements are implemented in the response and check them off as you add them.** #### **** **Note: For the rewrite step you may use Deepseek V3 to help you further improve the code. You cannot use any other model to assist you in any way possible. The same for restructuring/paraphrasing the turn 5 response as if it was a direct response to the target prompt.**

**Also make sure:** **You are using Typescript for React tasks** The most common way contributors mess up is by using JavaScript instead of TypeScript for React tasks. They often also forget to add Typescript typing. You can literally just ask the model to generate the typing for you using process supervision. **You are using Tailwind CSS** Projects that use Tailwind produces code that is easier to read and edit in a single file. This makes it easier to score a 5. It's a strict requirement that every task uses Tailwind. **You are using Component Libraries, Icon Libraries, and Other Useful Packages** It is easier to design visually impressive UIs by leveraging existing libraries. We recommend using the following packages to enhance your UI: 1. react-icons 2. lucide-react 3. motion 4. shadcn-ui 5. recharts **Before proceeding, always check for logic errors** If your app has logic errors, for example wrongly functioning menus, buttons etc (something unexpected happens or it doesn't work at all), you must fix your code. Make sure to check for edge cases to prevent getting a bad score.

sections.title: Golden Design Quality - How to score a 5/5

contents.body: **3.1 WRITE THE GOLDEN RESPONSE (Design quality)** Responses must **demonstrate a significantly improved visual output,** while maintaining distinctiveness and originality compared to Claude 3.7 Sonnet Extended or GPT 4.1, to be considered for submission. **TL;DR: It needs to be miles ahead of Claude 3.7 Sonnet Extended / GPT 4.1.**

You should first design your UI and then add functionality. It‚Äôs best practice to create the layout first using Grids, Flex boxes, etc and then fill up the content. Leverage the utility classes of Tailwind to the fullest.

Step

Description

Step 1 - Pick a design trend

Each task should have a specific trending design trend. First pick one of the design trends mentioned here:

Visual Design Trends and then look for inspiration on dribble.com. Here we're showcasing an example of the neumorphism trend: https://dribbble.com/tags/neumorphism. Dribble contains many cool examples you should use as a baseline. What you develop must be equally visually appealing as a dribbble submission.

Step 2 - Use a good looking font other than the default font

Using the default font automatically looks bad and reduces your score. If you use the default font, we have to fix it. If you use Tailwind CSS, you can change the font very easily.

Step 3 - Add visualizations

Add Visualizations from open-source websites. A good open source website to get visuals from is https://unsplash.com. There are many other open source websites you can use for visuals. Ensure that the images are open-source! Not adding visualizations is an extremely common reason for failure.

Step 4 - Use a good font hierarchy

Font hierarchy allows users to visually separate out which elements are more important. Use a combination of font weight and font size to create a good font hierarchy. Lack of font hierarchy will reduce your score.

Step 5 - Choose a color palette

If you pick random colors without thought, your design will look unprofessional. Choose a matching color palette using a tool like: https://coolors.co/generate

Step 6 - Make sure your app isn't too dull

Even if you have a nice color palette, if you don't use them on enough elements your design will look dull. Try adding color to titles, subtitles, borders, on hovers or try adding dots for accents.

Step 7 - Make sure your elements have enough contrast

If it is hard to read the text or distinguish elements from each other because there isn't enough contrast, you will receive a lower score. Make sure your app has decent contrast.

Step 8 - Make sure spacing is consistent and well spaced

If the elements are too close to each other, it looks cluttered and you will get a lower score. If the elements are too far apart and there is too much empty space you will also get a lower score. Make sure to carefully choose how you space your elements and also make sure it's consistent.

Step 9 - Make sure your layout looks complete

Websites look better when they look complete. Even if you're creating a small widget, try to center it in the whole page and give the package a colorful background. This will make your design look more complete and professional, making it easier to get a higher score.

Step 10 - Make sure your layout is minimalistic

Never have a large title in the center of your screen. A minimalistic layout focuses on clarity, usability, and removing unnecessary elements that do not serve a functional purpose. To achieve this, use plenty of white space, a limited color palette, simple typography, and a clear visual hierarchy. A great example is Apple‚Äôs website, which emphasizes clean design, subtle elements, and a focus on content.

Step 11 - Add Micro Transactions

Add tiny design details‚Äîlike button animations, loading indicators, or sound effects‚Äîthat provide users with immediate feedback, making interfaces feel more responsive and intuitive.

I'm ready to submit this task and show it to the project team ‚úÖ ‚ÄúYes‚Äù ->All explicit requirements for the target prompt have been strictly fulfilled. Nothing was left out ‚úÖ ‚ÄúYes‚Äù ->All implicit requirements (not explictly mentioned) have autonomously been determined and implemented by me. ‚úÖ ‚ÄúYes‚Äù ->This is the best I can do as a Front End Developer. This is something I would add to my portfolio and this shows why I'm a professional. **6.Collect data on the Golden Response and reevaluate (post process supervision)** **6a**: Once a "Golden Response" that ranks ‚â•4 in each dimension and beats the both SOTA responses at the start by 1000 miles) is obtained, click the "End Session" button. The UI must look like a commercial UI of a 2025 Fortune 500 company. **6b**: Capture a final screenshot of the visual output for the Golden Response. **6c**: Write a detailed justification explaining clearly and specifically why the response scores at least 4 for each dimension. Then, submit the final justification along with the screenshot to finalize and complete the task.¬† ***üö®Note: Please triple check your work and ensure the UI looks amazing and production ready. You can restart the conversation using the circular arrow if upon revision you must fix your mistakes*** **7.Review Your Work Using The Quality Control Spec Doc For Attempters** **STOP BEFORE SUBMISSION** **7a:** Before submitting the task you need to review your work using the attempter quality control spec doc: [ Andromeda UI Qality Control Spec Doc Attempters ](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1g80IZ65YQ8heJu4gtJ7rE5OL1WyJwaMA8cB3Ci_ofus/edit?tab=t.7ej594sqz7z0) **7b:** Fix everything you do to ensure your task is scored at least a 4 for all rubrics else you risk being removed from the project.
You will view these steps in the task as follows:

Granular details matter and can lead to tasks failing. Following Instructions explicitly mentioned in a prompt is mandatory. Pay extra attention to what the requirements are. Use the rubric checklist from the Prompt Rubric Generator to identify every explicit

Error 1: Mismatched Label Text 

Please follow the explicit ask in the prompt, if the prompt ask for specific labels, please use the exact same labels

Lets look at the example below

  • Prompt says: "Build a project management UI with tabs for 'Started', 'In Progress', and 'Completed' tasks." 

  • In the UI, the final tab is labeled ‚ÄúDone‚Äù instead of ‚ÄúCompleted.‚Äù

Why this fails: Even small changes to explicit text (like button labels or tab names) can break prompt alignment. The model is being trained to follow exact instructions, changing wording undermines that goal. it would even fail if you mention ‚ÄúComplete‚Äù instead of ‚ÄúCompleted‚Äù. So be extra careful with the details

How to fix - Use the exact copy provided in the prompt. If it says ‚ÄúCompleted,‚Äù label it ‚ÄúCompleted.‚Äù, not ‚ÄúComplete‚Äù, you the exact Copy. Using ‚ÄúComplete‚Äù would also fail the task

contents.question: Which of the following would cause a task to fail due to misalignment with explicit prompt instructions?

choices.answer: Using ‚ÄúComplete‚Äù instead of ‚ÄúCompleted‚Äù for a task status tab
Replacing a ‚ÄúStart‚Äù button with ‚ÄúBegin‚Äù
Adding an extra ‚ÄúSettings‚Äù tab that wasn‚Äôt mentioned in the prompt
Keeping button and tab labels exactly as described in the prompt
Changing ‚ÄúCheckout‚Äù to ‚ÄúBuy Now‚Äù for clearer wording

contents.body:
Error 2: Incomplete Features and Functionality

  • Your UI should work like a real app, not just a static demo

  • You should make sure the feature you add are fully functional and work as intended

Lets look at an example:

Prompt: Create an event showcase layout using Next.js that highlights upcoming creative workshops and design exhibits. Include features such as an event calendar, RSVP functionality, and detailed event pages. Emphasize visual attractiveness and ease of navigation, ensuring compatibility across web platforms.

  • UI Link

What the UI did:

  • RSVP shows a confirmation message but doesn‚Äôt update attendee count

  • Clicking on events only enlarges the image with a description‚Äîno dedicated event detail pages

  • Event calendar present, but limited interaction

Why this fails: 

  • RSVP feature is half-broken‚Äîconfirmation without state update fails Feature Completeness

  • Detailed event pages are missing entirely, violating an explicit prompt requirement
    Enlarging an image is not equivalent to a proper event page with full detail

How to Fix

  • Implement RSVP logic that updates attendee count or reflects participation in UI (even if mocked)

  • Link each event to a separate page or modal with full event info‚Äîlocation, time, description, image

  • Use dynamic routing in Next.js to support per-event pages ( /events/[id].tsx), even with placeholder data

Error 3: Using Images with Copyright Issues

As part of building beautiful UIs, you're expected to use relevant stock images that match the content and context. Please avoid using any logos, icons, or assets from trademarked companies. This includes logos from brands like Nike, Apple, Google, etc. Avoid using brand icons or styles that could resemble trademarked designs

Lets look at the following example:

While this seems like a perfectly good picture of friends hanging out, the person in the black shirt is wearing a puma logo. This task would fail for copyright issues

Image 2

 While it's common to see sign ups from leading companies. It is good practice to avoid these icons of trademarked companies. Use Placeholders instead

contents.question: Which of the following practices violates the project's copyright and intellectual property guidelines? Select all that apply

choices.answer: A) Using a grey square labeled ‚ÄúLogo‚Äù in place of a real brand icon
B) Including a Nike logo in the corner of the header for visual polish
C) Using <PlaceholderIcon /> as a stand-in for branded content
D) Importing and using Lucide React Icons for visual design

contents.explanation: Correct Answer: option B and D. Justification: B)  Violation: Using real brand logos (like Nike) is a direct copyright/IP violation and must be avoided.  D) Lucide React Icons, while open source, fall under restricted usage for this project to prevent branding look alike or licensing issues.

contents.body:
Error 4: Static ‚ÄúComing Soon‚Äù Features

  • You add extra buttons or features not in the prompt‚Äîlike ‚ÄúInvite Team‚Äù or ‚ÄúNotifications‚Äù‚Äîbut label them ‚ÄúComing Soon‚Äù or leave them non-functional.

  • Why this fails: You‚Äôre cluttering the UI with non-working features the model is not expected to learn from. These confuse both users and the training model.

    • How to Fix: Only include what the prompt requests. If you go beyond, make sure it's fully implemented and useful.

contents.question: You want to add a feature, but instead, you include a non-functional button labeled ‚ÄúComing soon.‚Äù In which of the following scenarios is this acceptable?

choices.answer: 1. When the prompt explicitly requests a "coming soon" feature
1. When you are short on time and want to avoid losing the task
1. Don‚Äôt use ‚ÄúComing Soon‚Äù placeholders
1. When you feel the feature was implied in the prompt

contents.explanation: Correct Answer: Don‚Äôt use ‚ÄúComing Soon‚Äù placeholders. Justification: Prompts asking for non-functional ‚ÄúComing Soon‚Äù features are often misused to avoid quality check failures.  Adding non-working elements clutters the UI and introduces noise that confuses both users and the model‚Äîit doesn‚Äôt help the model learn meaningful behavior.
